\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to get a beam of light to interfere with itself is via the use
 of a configuration of optical devices commonly known as the Michelson interfero
meter, after the American physicist Albert A.
 Michelson.
 A beam of light is incident on a beam splitter, where it is divided into
 two beams that travel at right angles with respect to each other.
 Two flat mirrors that face the beam splitter are placed such that they
 reflect each of the beams back towards the beam splitter, where they are
 both transmitted in the same direction.
 By adjusting the length of each of the arms of the interferometer, one
 can introduce a phase difference between the two beams that becomes apparent
 once they recombine.
 Because one of the beams passes through the beam splitter three times,
 and the other passes through it only once, it is common practice to introduce
 a compensating plate made of a transparent material in the propagation
 path of the second beam, in order to correct for this path difference,
 and make it depend exclusively on the relative position of each of the
 mirrors.
 It is also possible to place a converging lens before the beam stopper
 in order to bring the two beams into focus.
 This arrangement is shown in Figure 4.
 If a photosensor is placed at the beam stopper (P in the figure), the measured
 intensity is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I=I_{1}+I_{2}+2\sqrt{I_{1}I_{2}}\cos\delta
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 correspond to the intensity of each of the beams, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the phase difference, which is related to the lengths of each of the
 arms 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{2}$
\end_inset

 by the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta=\frac{4\pi c}{\nu_{0}}(n_{1}l_{1}-n_{2}l_{2})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}$
\end_inset

 correspond to the refractive indices of the medium constituting each of
 the interferometer arms, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the frequency of the light in vaccum.
 For the case of an interferometer that uses a 50/50 beam splitter, and
 where the beams propagate through air, we can write the intensity as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I=I_{0}\left[1+\cos\left(\frac{4\pi c}{\nu_{0}}(l_{1}-l_{2})\right)\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Changing the position of either of the mirrors by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 results in a change in the intensity given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I=I_{0}\left[1+\cos\left(\frac{4\pi c\Delta x}{\nu_{0}}\right)\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the case of light that is not completely monochromatic, as is the case
 of laser light, the intensity curve is more complicated, since the different
 frequencies interfere to produce a beat effect.
 For the particular case of the laser beam used in this project, we expect
 there to be two axial modes of equal polarization separated by a frequency
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu$
\end_inset

, that will interfere with each other.
 In that case, we can derive the intensity measured by the photodetector
 by regarding the laser light as a superposition of two monochromatic waves,
 each one corresponding to one of the modes of oscillation.
 This implies that the interference now happens between four different waves.
 The electric field at the photosensor is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=E_{1}+E_{2}+E_{3}+E_{4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intensity is proportional to the square modulus of this sum,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left|E\right|^{2} & = & (E_{1}+E_{2}+E_{3}+E_{4})(E_{1}^{*}+E_{2}^{*}+E_{3}^{*}+E_{4}^{*})\nonumber \\
 & = & \left|E_{1}\right|^{2}+\left|E_{2}\right|^{2}+\left|E_{3}\right|^{2}+\left|E_{4}\right|^{2}+2Re(E_{1}E_{2}^{*})+2Re(E_{1}E_{3}^{*})\nonumber \\
 &  & +2Re(E_{1}E_{4}^{*})+2Re(E_{2}E_{3}^{*})+2Re(E_{2}E_{4}^{*})+2Re(E_{3}E_{4}^{*})
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following [5], we can write the time-averaged electric fields as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
E_{1} & = & E_{01}e^{ik_{1}x}\nonumber \\
E_{2} & = & E_{01}e^{ik_{1}(x+2\Delta x)}\nonumber \\
E_{3} & = & E_{02}e^{ik_{2}x}\nonumber \\
E_{4} & = & E_{02}e^{ik_{2}(x+2\Delta x)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\frac{2\pi}{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, the wavenumber of the mode.
 Substituting into (12), and after performing some trigonometric algebra,
 we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left|E\right|^{2} & = & 2\left[E_{01}^{2}+E_{02}^{2}+E_{01}^{2}\cos(2k_{1}\Delta x)+E_{02}^{2}\cos(2k_{2}\Delta x)\right.\nonumber \\
 &  & \left.+4E_{01}E_{02}\cos\left(k_{1}\Delta x\right)\cos\left(k_{2}\Delta x\right)\cos\left((k_{1}-k_{2})(\Delta x+2x)\right)\right]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\frac{E_{01}}{E_{02}}$
\end_inset

, and rewrite this as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
I\propto\frac{1}{2}\left|\frac{E}{E_{02}}\right|^{2} & = & 1+a^{2}+a\cos(2k_{1}\Delta x)+\cos(2k_{2}\Delta x)\nonumber \\
 &  & +4a\cos\left(k_{1}\Delta x\right)\cos\left(k_{2}\Delta x\right)\cos\left((k_{1}-k_{2})(\Delta x+2x)\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $2x$
\end_inset

 factor in the last term is just an offset that does not affect the shape
 of the curve, so we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Rewriting in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu$
\end_inset

, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
I & \propto & 1+a^{2}+a\cos\left(\frac{4\pi\nu_{0}\Delta x}{c}\right)+\cos\left(\frac{4\pi(\nu_{0}+\Delta\nu)\Delta x}{c}\right)\nonumber \\
 &  & +4a\cos\left(\frac{2\pi\nu_{0}\Delta x}{c}\right)\cos\left(\frac{2\pi(\nu_{0}+\Delta\nu)\Delta x}{c}\right)\cos\left(\frac{2\pi\Delta\nu\Delta x}{c}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The frequency separation of the laser modes depends on the length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 of the laser cavity, and is given by the simple expression
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\nu=\frac{c}{2L}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For an HeNe laser with nominal wavelength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}=632.8$
\end_inset

 nm, and cavity length 
\begin_inset Formula $L=10$
\end_inset

 cm, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}=4.74\times10^{14}$
\end_inset

 Hz and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu=\frac{c}{2L}=1.50\times10^{9}$
\end_inset

 Hz.
 Figure 5 shows a plot of (16) after normalization, using these values,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1$
\end_inset

.
 As can be seen, the distance between the peaks of the modulating sinusoid
 corresponds to the length of the laser cavity.
 In practice, it is very difficult to experimentally recreate such a curve,
 because the high frequency of the light implies that the oscillations in
 the intensity are extremely sensitive to changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

.
 For this reason, if the goal is to experimentally determine 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu$
\end_inset

, it is more convenient to do so by constructing a so called visibility
 curve.
 The interference effects give rise to a fringe pattern, and a measure of
 the contrast of this pattern is the visibility, which is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{V}=\frac{I_{max}-I_{min}}{I_{max}+I_{min}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Essentially, this is a measure of the difference in intensity between the
 contiguous minima and maxima of the intensity curve.
 Obtaining a general formula for the visibility as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 is not as straightforward as obtaining the one for the intensity, especially
 if the relative intensities of the modes is not known.
 Figure 6 shows visibility curves for different kinds of quasimonochromatic
 light.
 A more detailed treatment of this topic is outside the scope of this work,
 and can be found in chapter VII of [4].
 For the purposes of this project, it is enough to say that if the difference
 in the relative mode intensities is large enough, we expect the visibility
 curve at some distance away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x=0$
\end_inset

 to be well approximated by a damped sinusoid, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{V}(\Delta x)\approx\alpha e^{-\beta\Delta x}\sin(\gamma\Delta x+\epsilon)+\eta
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 are free parameters that depend on the intensities of the modes and on
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu$
\end_inset

.
 We explicitly write 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\nu=\frac{c\gamma}{16\pi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

