\begin_layout Standard
This experiment uses the Lloyd's mirror technique to recreate Young's double
 slit experiment without the need to use a screen with two apertures.
 We set up a spatial filter using a 25 mm lens to focus the laser light
 into a pinhole located at its focal distance.
 We now mount a mirror in a rotation stage a small distance away from the
 spatial filter and rotate it such that the incident light is incident on
 the mirror at an angle close to 
\begin_inset Formula $90^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the mirror's surface normal.
 Careful rotation of the mirror into this position enables the transformation
 of a single point source into two point sources.
 Next, we place a 40 cm lens at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{o}>40$
\end_inset

 cm from the mirror, and place a screen at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}$
\end_inset

 from the lens corresponding to the mirror's image plane, which is related
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{o}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by the thin lens equation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{1}{d_{i}}=\nicefrac{1}{f}-\nicefrac{1}{d_{o}}$
\end_inset

.
 We now measure the separation 
\begin_inset Formula $a'$
\end_inset

 between the two point sources at the screen, and use this to find the source
 separation 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\frac{a'd_{0}}{d_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we remove the 40 cm lens in order to obtain the interference pattern
 at the screen and measure the separation of the vertical fringes 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta y$
\end_inset

.
 A diagram of the setup is shown in Figure 12, and a picture of the interference
 fringes is shown in Figure 13.
\end_layout

